  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The poet finds himself in the midst of circumstances gloomy in the extreme, but he does not despair; he still turns towards Jahve with his complaints, and calls Him the God of his salvation. This actus directus of fleeing in prayer to the God of salvation, which urges its way through all that is dark and gloomy, is the fundamental characteristic of all true faith. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 88:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not to be rendered, as a clause of itself: \"by day I cry unto Thee, in the night before Thee\" (lxx and Targum), which ought to have been יומם, but (as it is also pointed, especially in Baer's text): by day, i.e., in the time (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 56:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 78:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), when I cry before Thee in the night, let my prayer come... (Hitzig). In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 88:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he calls his piercing lamentation, his wailing supplication, רנּתי, as in ",
        "children": []
